The exemptions for rooming-in and breastfeeding are outlined in Republic Act No. 10028, also known as the "Expanded Breastfeeding Promotion Act of 2009". Specifically, Section 6 of the law states:

"Section 6. Rooming-In and Breastfeeding. - All health and non-health facilities and institutions shall establish lactation stations or areas where mothers can breastfeed or express milk in private which are conveniently accessible to persons who may use them. The lactation stations or areas shall be adequately provided with the necessary equipment and facilities, such as: lavatory for hand-washing; refrigeration or appropriate cooling facilities for storing breast milk; electrical outlets for breast pumps; a small table; comfortable seats; and other items as may be prescribed by the Department of Health (DOH) in consultation with the National Nutrition Council (NNC).

Rooming-in shall be practiced in all health and non-health facilities and institutions with delivery services, whether public or private, except under the following instances:

(a) when the infant's condition or the mother's health so warrants as certified by a duly licensed physician;

(b) when early discharge is requested by the mother provided that she and the infant are assessed and found to be clinically safe for such discharge by a duly licensed physician;

(c) when the infant is admitted to the Neonatal Intensive Care Unit (NICU);

(d) when the mother refuses to room-in;

(e) when the mother is discharged from the hospital;

(f) under other similar circumstances as may be determined by the DOH in consultation with the NNC." 

So all the options are included in the exemptions for rooming-in and breastfeeding.

